Exploring the Gender Gap in College Degrees

This project utilizes a data set regarding college degrees earned by women to visualize the gender gap in college degrees. The first steps involve importing pandas and matplot libraries, as well as reading the file.

The degrees are categorized according to whether they are STEM degrees, liberal arts degrees, or other degrees. The following code creates plots for the percentage of women and men in each of the degrees from 1970 to 2010.

In [13]:
%matplotlib inline
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

women_degrees = pd.read_csv('percent-bachelors-degrees-women-usa.csv')
cb_dark_blue = (0/255,107/255,164/255)
cb_orange = (255/255, 128/255, 14/255)

stem_cats = ['Psychology', 'Biology', 'Math and Statistics', 'Physical Sciences', 'Computer Science', 'Engineering']
lib_arts_cats = ['Foreign Languages', 'English', 'Communications and Journalism', 'Art and Performance', 'Social Sciences and History']
other_cats = ['Health Professions', 'Public Administration', 'Education', 'Agriculture','Business', 'Architecture']

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,20))

for sp in range(0,18,3):
    cat_index = int(sp/3)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,sp+1)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[stem_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_dark_blue, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[stem_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_orange, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(stem_cats[cat_index])
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", left="off", right="off")
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2005, 87, 'Women')
        ax.text(2005, 8, 'Men')
    elif cat_index == 5:
        ax.text(2005, 90, 'Men')
        ax.text(2001, 10, 'Women')

for sp in range(1,16,3):
    cat_index = int((sp-1)/3)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,sp+1)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[lib_arts_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_dark_blue, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[lib_arts_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_orange, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(lib_arts_cats[cat_index])
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", left="off", right="off")
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2005, 87, 'Women')
        ax.text(2002, 8, 'Men')
            

for sp in range(2,18,3):
    cat_index = int((sp-2)/3)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,sp+1)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[other_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_dark_blue, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[other_cats[cat_index]], c=cb_orange, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(other_cats[cat_index])
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", left="off", right="off")
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2005, 90, 'Women')
        ax.text(2005, 5, 'Men')
    elif cat_index == 5:
        ax.text(2005, 62, 'Men')
        ax.text(2005, 30, 'Women')

plt.show()

Removing Bottom Labels to Improve Readability

The following code removes the bottom labels to improve readability.

Examination of the plots reveals that, from 1970 to 2010, women have lessened the "gender gap" in the STEM fields of psychology, biology, and physical sciences, but the high-paying professions of computer science and engineering remain primarily male. Liberal arts degrees earned have remained relatively unchanged between women and men, while women have essentially closed the gap in agriculture, business, and architecture degrees.
